No problem about naming it. It's a good place: decent, home-made (and
it is!) food at sensible prices. Nice enough clientelle. It's a proper
local with regular punters. No daft kids. Friendly gaffer...

It's The Half Brick: on Brighton Road (i.e. just over the road from
the beach) at the bottom of Ham Road. Pretty good music venue: Bob,
the gaffer, is a pretty handy blues harp player and bluesy/gospelly
vocalist and fronts a band which seems to get around a bit, so he's a
keen supporter of live music. There's live music most nights, and he's
trying to build up Wednesdays as some sort of folk thing. I hope to be
doing one such in the vague future. Although I'm slightly anxious: he
keeps using the word &quot;hoolie&quot; about it, and I'm a bit too laid back
for that. But he knows my style - even if he hasn't heard my core
repertoire as yet - so I reckon I'll be okay.

--
Hamish

p.s. and, Chris, yes they do have a large covered patio area. The pub
was at least as busy as the other two times I went pre-ban.
